      <hedline>
        <hl1>Bob Knight and Society</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Howard Schain letter on May 16 article scores Indiana University's failure to dismiss basketball coach Bob Knight</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Retaining Bob Knight, the abusive basketball coach at Indiana University, with a slap on the wrist (editorial, May 16) for infractions that would result in dismissal, not to mention criminal prosecution, in any industry but sports sends the message that winning is valued above rules, civil behavior and common decency.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Retaining Bob Knight, the abusive basketball coach at Indiana University, with a slap on the wrist (editorial, May 16) for infractions that would result in dismissal, not to mention criminal prosecution, in any industry but sports sends the message that winning is valued above rules, civil behavior and common decency.</p>
        <p>This clear result of America's obsession with sports is both reflective of and instructive to the society at large (especially the children) and can be seen daily in the business community.</p>
        <p>While the competitive spirit is healthy and has helped make America the world economic power that it is, it turns destructive when it exceeds the bounds of ethics in any endeavor.</p>
        <p>HOWARD SCHAIN  New York, May 17, 2000</p>
      </block>
